<subSubSection id="C3586549FFC4FFCEA9F11C0A8698F8F6" pageId="2" pageNumber="545" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BFD36C2FFC4FFCEA9F11C0A8698F8F6" blockId="2.[151,1436,1765,1936]" pageId="2" pageNumber="545">
<emphasis id="B936EAD0FFC4FFCEA9F11C0A8350F8B9" bold="true" box="[199,328,1801,1827]" pageId="2" pageNumber="545">Etymology</emphasis>
. The generic name is derived from that of the Qin Dynasty in Chinese history, meaning old, combined with the Latinised suffix “ 
<emphasis id="B936EAD0FFC4FFCEA8801C2D8014F8DD" box="[438,524,1838,1863]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="545">-coccus</emphasis>
” (which stems from the Greek masculine noun κόκκος (
<emphasis id="B936EAD0FFC4FFCEAD411C2D86DBF8D2" box="[1143,1219,1838,1864]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="545">cóccos</emphasis>
) meaning “berry”), referring to the spherical, ovoid, or generally rounded shape of the adult female prosoma.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3586549FFC4FFCEA9F11C7680A6F80A" box="[199,702,1909,1936]" pageId="2" pageNumber="545" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BFD36C2FFC4FFCEA9F11C7680A6F80A" blockId="2.[151,1436,1765,1936]" box="[199,702,1909,1936]" pageId="2" pageNumber="545">
<emphasis id="B936EAD0FFC4FFCEA9F11C768331F815" bold="true" box="[199,297,1909,1935]" pageId="2" pageNumber="545">Remark</emphasis>
. The genus is monotypic at present.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
